First, the BIG idea (this will unlock everything)
HTML elements fall into two main types:

🔹 Block-level elements
👉 Take full width
👉 Start on a new line
👉 Used for big sections / structure

🔹 Inline elements
👉 Take only required space
👉 Stay in the same line
👉 Used for small parts inside text

div — big container (block-level)
Think of div as a box 📦
<div>
  <h2>My Studies</h2>
  <p>I am learning HTML and JavaScript</p>
</div>

What div means:
Groups multiple elements
Used for layout or sections
No meaning by itself (just a container)

👉 Use div when:
You have heading + paragraph
You want to apply CSS or JS to a group
You want to separate sections

✅ Correct thinking:
“This is a section of my page” → use div
span — small inline container (inline-level)
Think of span as a marker pen ✍️ inside text

<p>
  I am learning <span>JavaScript</span> now
</p>

What span means:
Wraps small text
Used inside text
Does NOT break the line

👉 Use span when:
You want to style one word or phrase
You want JS to target part of a sentence

❌ Wrong:
<span>
  <h1>Title</h1>
  <p>Paragraph</p>
</span>


✅ Right:
<p>
  My favorite subject is <span>Math</span>
</p>

Now your exact question 👇
“What if we have only a paragraph or only a heading?”

Case 1: Only a heading
<h2>My Studies</h2>
✅ No div needed

Case 2: Only a paragraph
<p>I am learning web development</p>
✅ No div needed

Case 3: Heading + paragraph (related content)
<div>
  <h2>My Studies</h2>
  <p>I am learning HTML, CSS, and JavaScript</p>
</div>
✅ Use div because they belong together

What about changes later?
This is IMPORTANT 👇
If tomorrow you want to:
Add another paragraph
Add a button
Add JS logic
Add styling
Then having a div helps a LOT:
<div id="studySection">
  <h2>My Studies</h2>
  <p>I am learning HTML</p>
</div>


JavaScript:
document.getElementById("studySection").style.background = "yellow";

💡 That’s why developers often wrap things in divs early
Simple decision rule (remember this 👇)
One element alone? → just use it (h, p)
Multiple related elements? → wrap in div
Small part of text? → use span

Super short summary ⭐
div → big block, groups elements
span → small inline part of text
h / p alone → no container needed


JavaScript reads, changes, deletes, adds HTML elements using DOM.

class: class is an attribute used to group multiple HTML elements under the same name, so they can be styled with CSS or accessed with JavaScript.

why class and why not id?
Because id is for ONE element, and class is for MANY elements.
🔴 Problem with using id everywhere
Example using id (WRONG way):
<p id="student">Alice</p>
<p id="student">Bob</p>
<p id="student">Charlie</p>


❌ This is invalid HTML

Why?

id must be unique

Browser behavior becomes unpredictable

JavaScript may select only the first one

✅ Correct way using class
<p class="student">Alice</p>
<p class="student">Bob</p>
<p class="student">Charlie</p>

✔ Valid
✔ Clean
✔ Scalable


What does onclick do?
<button onclick="changeText()">Click</button>

Means:
“When this button is clicked, call the function changeText()”


1️⃣ What is <script>?
<script> is an HTML tag used to write or connect JavaScript.
👉 Without <script>, JavaScript cannot run in HTML.

Two ways to use <script>
🔹 Way 1: Write JS inside HTML (inline script)
<script>
  console.log("Hello JavaScript");
</script>

JS is written inside the <script> tag
Good for learning & small examples

🔹 Way 2: External JavaScript file (BEST PRACTICE)
<script src="script.js"></script>
JS is written in script.js
HTML stays clean
Used in real projects

Important <script> attributes
1️⃣ src — source of JS file
<script src="app.js"></script>
👉 Tells browser:
“Load JavaScript from this file”

2️⃣ defer — run JS after HTML loads
<script src="app.js" defer></script>
👉 JS runs after HTML is parsed
Why important?
JS often accesses HTML elements
Prevents errors like null

3️⃣ async — load JS independently
<script src="app.js" async></script>
JS loads independently
Execution order is NOT guaranteed
Used for analytics, ads

Where should <script> be placed?
BEST & SIMPLE rule:
</body>
<script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
OR
<script src="script.js" defer></script>